e a custom validator, you must inherit from the abstract <xref:System.IdentityModel.Selectors.X509CertificateValidator> class."},{"content":"When creating a custom authenticator, the most important method to override is the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.IdentityModel.Selectors.X509CertificateValidator.Validate%2A&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[10737,10902],"source":"When creating a custom authenticator, the most important method to override is the <xref:System.IdentityModel.Selectors.X509CertificateValidator.Validate%2A> method."},{"content":"For an example of custom authentication, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>X.509 Certificate Validator<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../docs/framework/wcf/samples/x-509-certificate-validator.md)</ept> sample.","pos":[10903,11060],"source":" For an example of custom authentication, see the [X.509 Certificate Validator](../../../../docs/framework/wcf/samples/x-509-certificate-validator.md) sample."},{"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">[!INCLUDE[crdefault](../../../../includes/crdefault-md.md)]</ph><bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Custom Credential and Credential Validation<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../docs/framework/wcf/extending/custom-credential-and-credential-validation.md)</ept>.","pos":[11061,11255],"source":"[!INCLUDE[crdefault](../../../../includes/crdefault-md.md)][Custom Credential and Credential Validation](../../../../docs/framework/wcf/extending/custom-credential-and-credential-validation.md)."},{"pos":[11264,11311],"content":"Using Makecert.exe to Build a Certificate Chain","linkify":"Using Makecert.exe to Build a Certificate Chain","nodes":[{"content":"Using Makecert.exe to Build a Certificate Chain","pos":[0,47]}]},{"content":"The Certificate Creation Tool (Makecert.exe) creates X.509 certificates and private key/public key pairs.","pos":[11315,11420]},{"content":"You can save the private key to disk and then use it to issue and sign new certificates, thus simulating a hierarchy of chained certificates.","pos":[11421,11562]},{"content":"The tool is intended for use only as an aid when developing services and should never be used to create certificates for actual deployment.","pos":[11563,11702]},{"content":"When developing an <ph id=\"ph1\">[!INCLUDE[indigo2](../../../../includes/indigo2-md.md)]</ph> service, use the following steps to build a chain of trust with Makecert.exe.","pos":[11703,11855],"source":" When developing an [!INCLUDE[indigo2](../../../../includes/indigo2-md.md)] service, use the following steps to build a chain of trust with Makecert.exe."},{"pos":[11866,11909],"content":"To build a chain of trust with Makecert.exe","linkify":"To build a chain of trust with Makecert.exe","nodes":[{"content":"To build a chain of trust with Makecert.exe","pos":[0,43]}]},{"content":"Create a temporary root authority (self-signed) certificate using the MakeCert.exe tool.","pos":[11919,12007]},{"content":"Save the private key to the disk.","pos":[12008,12041]},{"content":"Use the new certificate to issue another certificate that contains the public key.","pos":[12051,12133]},{"content":"Import the root authority certificate into the Trusted Root Certification Authorities store.","pos":[12143,12235]},{"pos":[12245,12462],"content":"For step-by-step instructions, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>How to: Create Temporary Certificates for Use During Development<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../docs/framework/wcf/feature-details/how-to-create-temporary-certificates-for-use-during-development.md)</ept>.","source":"For step-by-step instructions, see [How to: Create Temporary Certificates for Use During Development](../../../../docs/framework/wcf/feature-details/how-to-create-temporary-certificates-for-use-during-development.md)."},{"pos":[12471,12496],"content":"Which Certificate to Use?","linkify":"Which Certificate to Use?","nodes":[{"content":"Which Certificate to Use?","pos":[0,25]}]},{"content":"Common questions about certificates are which certificate to use, and why.","pos":[12500,12574]},{"content":"The answer depends on whether you are programming a client or service.","pos":[12575,12645]},{"content":"The following information provides a general guideline and is not an exhaustive answer to these questions.","pos":[12646,12752]},{"pos":[12762,12782],"content":"Service Certificates","linkify":"Service Certificates","nodes":[{"content":"Service Certificates","pos":[0,20]}]},{"content":"Service certificates have the primary task of authenticating the server to clients.","pos":[12786,12869]},{"content":"One of the initial checks when a client authenticates a server is to compare the value of the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Subject<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> field to the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) used to contact the service: the DNS of both must match.","pos":[12870,13079],"source":" One of the initial checks when a client authenticates a server is to compare the value of the **Subject** field to the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) used to contact the service: the DNS of both must match."},{"content":"For example, if the URI of the service is \"<ph id=\"ph1\">http://www.contoso.com/endpoint/</ph>\" then the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Subject<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> field must also contain the value \"www.contoso.com\".","pos":[13080,13230],"source":" For example, if the URI of the service is \"http://www.contoso.com/endpoint/\" then the **Subject** field must also contain the value \"www.contoso.com\"."},{"content":"Note that the field can contain several values, each prefixed with an initialization to indicate the value.","pos":[13237,13344]},{"content":"Most commonly, the initialization is \"CN\" for common name, for example, \"CN = www.contoso.com\".","pos":[13345,13440]},{"content":"It is also possible for the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Subject<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> field to be blank, in which case the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Subject Alternative Name<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> field can contain the <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>DNS Name<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> value.","pos":[13441,13588],"source":" It is also possible for the **Subject** field to be blank, in which case the **Subject Alternative Name** field can contain the **DNS Name** value."},{"pos":[13595,13765],"content":"Also note the value of the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Intended Purposes<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> field of the certificate should include an appropriate value, such as \"Server Authentication\" or \"Client Authentication\".","source":"Also note the value of the **Intended Purposes** field of the certificate should include an appropriate value, such as \"Server Authentication\" or \"Client Authentication\"."},{"pos":[13775,13794],"content":"Client Certificates","linkify":"Client Certificates","nodes":[{"content":"Client Certificates","pos":[0,19]}]},{"content":"Client certificates are not typically issued by a third-party certification authority.","pos":[13798,13884]},{"content":"Instead, the Personal store of the current user location typically contains certificates placed there by a root authority, with an intended purpose of \"Client Authentication\".","pos":[13885,14060]},{"content":"The client can use such a certificate when mutual authentication is required.","pos":[14061,14138]},{"pos":[14147,14187],"content":"Online Revocation and Offline Revocation","linkify":"Online Revocation and Offline Revocation","nodes":[{"content":"Online Revocation and Offline Revocation","pos":[0,40]}]},{"pos":[14197,14217],"content":"Certificate Validity","linkify":"Certificate Validity","nodes":[{"content":"Certificate Validity","pos":[0,20]}]},{"content":"Every certificate is valid only for a given period of time, called the <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>validity period<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.","pos":[14221,14310],"source":"Every certificate is valid only for a given period of time, called the *validity period*."},{"content":"The validity period is defined by the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Valid from<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Valid to<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> fields of an X.509 certificate.","pos":[14311,14412],"source":" The validity period is defined by the **Valid from** and **Valid to** fields of an X.509 certificate."},{"content":"During authentication, the certificate is checked to determine whether the certificate is still within the validity period.","pos":[14413,14536]},{"pos":[14546,14573],"content":"Certificate Revocation List","linkify":"Certificate Revocation List","nodes":[{"content":"Certificate Revocation List","pos":[0,27]}]},{"content":"At any time during the validity period, the certification authority can revoke a certificate.","pos":[14577,14670]},{"content":"This can occur for many reasons, such as a compromise of the private key of the certificate.","pos":[14671,14763]},{"content":"When this occurs, any chains that descend from the revoked certificate are also invalid, and are not trusted during authentication procedures.","pos":[14770,14912]},{"content":"To find out which certificates are revoked, each issuer publishes a time- and date-stamped <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>certificate revocation list<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> (CRL).","pos":[14913,15040],"source":" To find out which certificates are revoked, each issuer publishes a time- and date-stamped *certificate revocation list* (CRL)."},{"content":"The list can be checked using either online revocation or offline revocation by setting the <ph id=\"ph1\">`RevocationMode`</ph> or <ph id=\"ph2\">`DefaultRevocationMode`</ph> property of the following classes to one of the <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Security.Cryptography.X509Certificates.X509RevocationMode&gt;</ph> enumeration values: <ph id=\"ph4\">&lt;xref:System.ServiceModel.Security.X509ClientCertificateAuthentication&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph5\">&lt;xref:System.ServiceModel.Security.X509PeerCertificateAuthentication&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph6\">&lt;xref:System.ServiceModel.Security.X509ServiceCertificateAuthentication&gt;</ph>, and the <ph id=\"ph7\">&lt;xref:System.ServiceModel.Security.IssuedTokenServiceCredential&gt;</ph> classes.","pos":[15041,1561